english:
  title: A Memorial Requesting the Suspension of Relocation of the Royal Residence
  author: Kwon Je
  language: eng
  text: "Your humble servant respectfully submits that Zhou Gong and Confucius were great sages. Zhou Gong created ritual and music, establishing laws that would endure for ten thousand generations. Confucius inherited the past and opened the future, transmitting teachings to all ages. Therefore, if one were to govern without following the example of Zhou Gong and Confucius, your servant cannot see how that could be right.\n\nConcerning the recent memorial submitted by Yang Shan, though I know not all its particulars, I have heard from others that he proposes the Seungmun Academy be the nation's sacred precinct, that Gyeongbok Palace is not such a place and must be relocated, and that if it is not, common folk might dwell there and produce heroes through earthly resonance—which would not benefit the state. Thus Your Majesty commanded great ministers to select auspicious sites, and ordered the Hall of Worthies to consult geographical texts in preparation.\n\nI know not from whence the doctrine of geomancy derives. If its predictions of fortune and misfortune prove true and bear such grave consequence for the nation's fate, then how is it that Zhou Gong and Confucius, with their profound concern for the realm and the world, uttered not a single word upon this matter? Was the originator of this doctrine wiser than Zhou Gong and Confucius?\n\nSima Guang and Zhu Xi were also great sages. Yet Sima Guang thoroughly refuted the doctrine of selecting burial sites by auspicious location, and Zhu Xi followed his reasoning. If geomancy is true, why did these wise men reject it? Thus it is evident that geomancy—unspoken by the sages, rejected by the great philosophers—is spurious and unworthy of belief. Yang Shan's learning is crude and unrefined, and therefore equally unworthy of trust.\n\nWhen first I heard of this matter, I believed Your Majesty would surely dismiss it. Yet hearing that great ministers have been commanded to survey the land, that the Hall of Worthies has been ordered to examine these texts, and that both high and low have become alarmed and swayed—I came to understand that even Your Majesty's sagacity has been touched by Yang Shan's claims of consequence. That the harm of such false doctrine could reach so deeply vexes me greatly.\n\nThough your servant is foolish and wished to lay bare his thoughts before the Dragon Throne, fear of the imperial presence prevented such boldness. This very month, a fever seized me—no light affliction—and for ten days I dared not venture to the palace. Unable to present my sincere concerns, I am overcome with anguish. Thus do I dare, at risk of imperial displeasure, to submit this humble view, beseeching Your Majesty's gracious consideration.\n\nThose who founded dynasties and established their succession possessed far-seeing vision and profound deliberation. Our Taejo's divine wisdom and sagacious calculation surpassed all his contemporaries and officials. Even a single royal proclamation was never issued lightly. How much more so the selection of a capital and the building of the palace—matters of great import? Would these not have been carefully deliberated? \n\nFlatterers and schemers seek advantage in what benefits the ruler, employing countless stratagems to move the sovereign's heart. Their words sound sincere and detailed, pleasant to the ear, yet prove ruinous in practice—often bringing later regret. Such is the common affliction of all ages. Who is Yang Shan? Should we now credit his shallow and scheming words while doubting what our Taejo established? This cannot be right.\n\nMoreover, if Yang Shan truly claims that heroes will emerge, is he not deliberately speaking in mysterious and unfathomable terms to move Your Majesty and achieve his designs? His cunning is evident.\n\nSince the cosmos began, how many dynasties have risen and fallen! In which age did the technique of suppressing auspicious sites ever prevent the emergence of heroes? If geomancy could truly suppress such emergence and ensure eternal succession, then surely Zhou Gong and Confucius would have practiced it first. Are we to believe them lacking wisdom or loyalty? Moreover, I have never read in the chronicles that any emperor was born in an auspicious location and thereby became ruler. Even granting such a principle true, heroes are born in countless places—how could all the nation's auspicious sites be suppressed and guarded?\n\nYour servant has long studied the rise and fall of past dynasties. Succeeding rulers, though foolish or mad, remained secure when their ancestors had built deep virtue and won the people's hearts. The people's hearts could not bear to abandon them, and Heaven likewise would not abandon them. Thus to ensure lasting succession, one need only employ deep virtue to firmly bind the people's hearts. This was true in the Three Dynasties and remains true from Han and Tang onward. Yet these truths Your Majesty already perceives clearly, so I shall not belabor them.\n\nOur Hanseong was mentioned in apocryphal texts. In the previous dynasty, attempts were made to suppress this through building palaces and royal progresses—many such efforts!—yet they could not prevent the rise of the present glorious age. If Heaven's Mandate truly exists, can mere human cunning prevent it?\n\nWhen Emperor Yang of Sui killed Li Quanya, yet the armies of Jinyang arose. When Emperor Shizong of Zhou killed Fang Mianda, yet the revolt at Chenqiao suddenly occurred. Despite Zhou's careful precautions, when his policies failed to benefit posterity, could they save him from ruin? History's clear lessons are manifest, yet Yang Shan seeks to bewitch Your Majesty with heterodox arts. He is among the basest of schemers.\n\nWell did Emperor Taizong of Tang speak: \"He who rules the realm need only rectify his person and cultivate virtue. All else is empty affair, unworthy of consideration.\" That one so wise perceived this truth! Yet Your Majesty, possessed of heaven-sent sagacity, falls short in this one regard. Your servant is deeply ashamed and deeply pained.\n\nConfucius said, \"To specialize in heterodox doctrines brings harm to oneself.\" Yet now the Hall of Worthies is commanded to lecture upon these texts for royal consultation—this astonishes me greatly! When Emperor Zhezong of Song had the Daoist Chen Jing'yuan edit Daoist texts, the minister Fan Zuyu protested that this damaged the dignity of the court. If even having a Daoist edit Daoist texts seemed improper when commanded by the sovereign, how much more so to have the ruler personally examine spurious and heterodox texts?\n\nWhen our Taizong wished to study the poetry of Du Fu, your servant's father Minister Geun objected that this was unfit for a ruler to learn, and requested instead lectures on the Book of Changes. The Taizong acceded. If even poetry seemed unsuitable, how could heterodox and absurd texts be lectured upon in the royal academy? \n\nMoreover, the ruler's learning differs fundamentally from the scholar's learning. How could a ruler attempt to master all the hundred schools and countless arts? This violates the very nature of royal scholarship. Your servant deeply fears this path for Your Majesty. Though Your Majesty's brightness makes learning easy and understanding harmless, should later rulers follow this precedent and fall prey to such doctrines, the harm would indeed be as the Master warned. Can this not be a cause for concern?\n\nYour servant knows that ultimately Your Majesty will not believe such doctrines. Yet that great ministers conduct these surveys and the Hall of Worthies conducts these lectures, causing such disorder among the people—this is no trifling matter. Your humble servant respectfully urges that Your Majesty uphold right principle and suppress false doctrines. Consider this foolish servant's loyal heart and cease the command for site selection. Suspend the lectures of the Hall of Worthies. Thus block the false doctrines and calm the people's hearts.\n\nIn grand matters, take Zhou Gong and Confucius as teachers. In near matters, follow the paths of Taejo and Taizong. Honor the Six Classics and reject the hundred schools. Correct the human heart and discern right from wrong. When virtue and moral transformation flow from above, filial piety, fraternal respect, loyalty, and honesty flourish below. When all people show reverence for their superiors and respect for their elders, the nation shall stand firm as stone.\n\nYour servant is by nature incompetent and lazy in learning. Though I wish to speak, my words lack form to move others' hearts. How could such humble words touch your exalted judgment? Yet my sincere love of my ruler and concern for the realm cannot be suppressed. Thus do I presume to submit this view, beseeching Your Majesty's gracious attention. Your servant Je remains in trembling awe, awaiting your commands."
  footnotes:
    - Seungmun Academy (承文院) - a royal educational institution
    - The Sage Kings Zhou Gong and Confucius are presented as the ultimate authorities on governance; any doctrine they did not teach should be suspect
    - Geomancy (풍수) - the Chinese belief system about placement and orientation based on natural features and spiritual forces
    - Emperor Taizong's dictum reflects Neo-Confucian emphasis on moral cultivation over external practices as the foundation of good rule
    - The memorial argues that if geomancy truly worked, it would be universally practiced by all wise rulers throughout history, yet the evidence shows otherwise
